Executive summary

This documents the use of demonstration validation artefacts that can be incorporated into one’s process of accepting ISO 20022 XML instances.

This environment is made freely available with no constraints on use and no responsibility or warranty of use.

1. Introduction

To make the validation of XML instances of select ISO 20022 schemas convenient, this environment provides Windows drag-and-drop, Windows command-line, and Shell command-line invocations.

ISO 20022 publishes a schema of hierarchy, granularity, cardinality, and lexical constraints that are imposed on XML documents to be considered valid ISO 20022 documents. Layered on top of those constraints are additional cardinality constraints imposed by the Business Payments Coalition (BPC) as a minimal set of value constraints. The committee may impose further cardinality and value constraints in the future.

The validation process involves two phases: W3C XML schema validation according to the untouched ISO 20022 XSD schema, and rule validation according to the BPC list of additional document constraints maintained in the committee’s Google spreadsheet as a set of ISO Schematron contexts and expressions.

Figure 1. Two-phase validation


The numbered artefacts depicted are as follows:

  1. W3C XML Schema XSD file as published by ISO 20022,

  2. W3C XSLT 2.0 stylesheet transforming the incoming XML document to a validation result by checking the BPC constraints,

  3. ISO/IEC 19757-3 Schematron schema of BPC constraints that is transformed into the XSLT used for validation, and

  4. ISO/IEC 26300 Open Document Format (ODF) spreadsheet ODS XML exported from the committee Google spreadsheet that is transformed into the Schematron schema.

Not shown in the diagram are an XSLT stylesheet that transforms the XML output of the depicted XSLT transformation into a simple text file and a validation true/false result, the XSLT stylesheets that transform the ODF into Schematron, and the XSLT stylesheets that transform the Schematron into XSLT.

2. Schemas

In the xsd/ subdirectory the all-iso-20022.xsd schema imports the selection of ISO 20022 schemas, also found in the xsd/ subdirectory.

At this time two different schemas are involved in the one validation: remt.001.001.05.xsd and remt.002.001.02.xsd.

3. Data integrity constraint checking

In the sch/ subdirectory the all-iso-20022.rules.sch Schematron schema declares all of the data integrity checks to be performed after successful XSD schema validation.

In the xsl/ subdirectory the all-iso-20022.rules.xsl XSLT stylesheet expresses the runtime implementation of the Schematron rules.

4. Validation files

The demonstration directory is the val/ directory:

  • *.xml - demonstration test files

  • *.jar - open-source project Java executables implementing validation and transformation (see the included notices for open-source details)

  • *.sh - Shell-based invocations in a *nix terminal

  • *.bat - Windows-based invocations in a DOS command box

  • windows-drag-n-drop/*.bat - Windows-based invocations using drag-n-drop functionality supporting dropping the XML file to be validated onto the batch file in Windows Explorer

  • testall.* - invocations for each of the files in the xml/ subdirectory

5. Java

Java must be installed in the environment before the demonstration can run or one can validate their own test files. To know if Java is ready to be used, one simply enters the command that brings up the “Usage:” summary:

C:\>java
Usage: java [-options] class [args...]
           (to execute a class)
   or  java [-options] -jar jarfile [args...]
           (to execute a jar file)
where options include:
...followed by many lines...

If the command cannot be found, an error message will be displayed.

6. Demonstration execution

A running Java-based demonstration of the two-phase ingestion of an ISO 20022 XML document is in the val/ subdirectory.

There are four illustrative XML instances being validated:

  • iso-20022-test-bad-syntax.xml - a document with an XML syntax error on line 9

    • the end delimiter of the closing tag for the MsgId element is missing

  • iso-20022-test-bad-model.xml - a document with a UBL model error on line 9

    • the expected date and time element contains only a date value

  • iso-20022-test-good.xml - a valid document without violating Schematron data integrity constraints

To run the demonstration there is an invocation for each of the Windows and Shell environments:

  • Windows command line:

    • cd val\
test.bat

  • Windows explorer:

    • double-click on test.bat to execute the program in a pop-up window (the batch file will pause at the end)

    • note that lengthy reports will scroll out of the history of window lines so they may not appear when scrolling back to find them (see Section 9, “Configuring Windows DOS box history” for details on increasing the length of the history)

  • Shell:

    • cd val/
sh test.sh

Also included is a script to run all of the document types in both of the customizations for both “good” and “bad” test files:

  • Windows command line:

    • cd val\
testall.bat

  • Windows explorer:

    • double-click on testall.bat to execute the program in a pop-up window (the batch file will pause at the end)

    • note that lengthy reports will scroll out of the history of window lines so they may not appear when scrolling back to find them (see Section 9, “Configuring Windows DOS box history” for details on increasing the length of the history)

  • Shell:

    • cd val/
sh testall.sh

7. Data errors and internal errors

When running the Schematron script, there are two kinds of reports: a data constraint error or an internal error.

A data constraint error report starts with an enumeration of the error, followed by the error message, followed by the context of the error, followed by " / ", followed by the failed rule expression.

Internal errors are of particular importance to the developers of the Schematron, as these reflect previously-undetected errors or improvements in the schema that should be repaired. These should be reported.

8. Validating one’s own test files

To validate a test document of one’s own that is found in your local computer file system there is a Java-based invocation for each of the Windows and Shell environments:

  • Windows drag-n-drop:

    • fully extract the nested ZIP files into your file system because drag-n-drop does not work from inside ZIP extractor virtual directories

    • open the unzipped val/windows-drag-n-drop/ directory in Windows Explorer to reveal the available invocations

    • drag your XML file from Windows Explorer where it is being edited, and drop it onto the corresponding invocation batch file performing the desired validation

      Figure 2. Windows Drag-n-Drop


    • a dynamic command DOS box window will open up revealing the results until a key is pressed to make the window disappear (see Section 9, “Configuring Windows DOS box history” for details on adjusting the length of the history)

      Figure 3. Windows Drop Execution


  • Windows DOS prompt:

    • validate-20022.bat xml-file

      for example from the test.bat demonstration:

      validate-20022.bat test.xml

  • Shell:

    • sh validate-20022.sh xml-file

      for example from the test.sh demonstration:

      sh validate-20022.sh test.xml

When there is an error of any kind, the script creates a file named by adding the “.error.txt” suffix to the input file name and records the error information in that file.

When there is a data integrity error, the script also creates a file named by adding the “.svrl.xml” suffix to the input file name and records the Schematron SVRL record information in that file.

For example, if one has a test file for customization ‘core’ named myISO20022Test.xml in the val\ directory then in Windows one would use:

validate-20022.bat myISO20022Test.xml

and when running from another directory one need only point to the invocation and schema:

Validate-20022-20221003-1440z\val\validate-20022.bat myISO20022Test.xml

And if one is using Shell in the val/ directory one would use:

sh validate-20022.sh myISO20022Test.xml

and when running from another directory one need only point to the invocation and schema:

sh Validate-20022-20221003-1440z/val/validate-20022.sh myISO20022Test.xml

9. Configuring Windows DOS box history

Should the dynamic command DOS box history be too short for a long report, the height of the box window (dictating the history) can be increased as follows:

  • execute any of the Windows batch files so that the dynamic DOS box is presented on the screen (do not press any key when the batch file finishes executing)

  • either left-click on the DOS box icon in the title bar, or right-click anywhere on the title bar

  • select “Properties”

  • click on the “Layout” tab

  • in the “Screen Buffer Size” set of values, change the “Height” value typing in a large number such as “2000”

  • click on the “OK” button

  • when the batch file finishes executing, press any key to exit

The next time the dynamic command DOS box is used, the new setting for the height will be in play. When the batch file completes execution, one can scroll up through the history to see the complete report.
